Gauteng Community Safety MEC Faith Mazibuko is pleading with residents to comply with regulations. Unlawful gatherings are an issue. Courtesy #DStv403 JOHANNESBURG - Gauteng Community Safety MEC, Faith Mazibuko is pleading with residents to comply with regulations. She says unlawful gatherings are an issue. READ: Tshwane municipality says large gatherings won't be tolerated Mazibuko said drinking and driving is a serious challenge for the province. "We wish to call upon our people in Gauteng to please comply with the disaster management regulations because they can save your life. Always remember to wear your masks, even when you're in your car and there is two or three of you, you must wear masks." The Gauteng Police Commissioner Elias Mawela says law enforcement is having problems with street parties across the province. - Coronavirus Hotline Number: 0800 029 999 from 8am to 4pm, Monday to Friday Help protect your loved ones by sharing this official South African government COVID-19 service with your family, friends and community. Send HI to 0600 123 456 on WhatsApp. The NICD has another Clinician Hotline to improve #COVID19 communication and support for healthcare providers. The Clinician Hotline is 0800 11 1131, operating 24 hrs. The Public Hotline is 0800 029 999 also operating 24hrs 